      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Help a Reporter Out, Connectively</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>HARO</strong> (Help a Reporter Out) is a platform where journalists post queries seeking expert sources for articles they are writing. SEOs and brand marketers respond to relevant queries with expert commentary. When a journalist selects your response, the published article includes a backlink to your website — often from publications with DR 60-90. It is one of the few link-building tactics that earns genuine editorial links from major news sites for free.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Link type</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Editorial (DA 30-90+)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO / Digital PR</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Response rate</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5-15% per pitch</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most SEOs trying HARO fail for a simple reason: they respond too slowly with generic answers. Journalists receive hundreds of responses per query and select sources within hours of posting. The marketers who consistently earn placements have a system — monitored inboxes, templated opening lines, and pre-approved expert responses ready to customise and send within 30 minutes.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is HARO?</h2>
        <p>HARO was founded in 2008 by Peter Shankman and was acquired by Cision in 2010. The original service sent journalist queries to registered sources via email three times daily (6 AM, 12 PM, and 5:30 PM EST). In 2023, Cision rebranded HARO as <strong>Connectively</strong>, moving to a platform-based model, though the core mechanic — journalist asks, source answers, journalist cites — remains the same.</p>
        <p>Competing platforms offering similar journalist-source matching include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Qwoted</strong> — favoured for finance and business press</li>
          <li><strong>Featured.com</strong> — question-and-answer format with editorial matching</li>
          <li><strong>JournoLink</strong> — UK-focused, strong for regional and trade press</li>
          <li><strong>SourceBottle</strong> — Australian-origin but global coverage</li>
          <li><strong>Terkel</strong> — expert contribution platform with publication network</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why HARO links are SEO-valuable</div>
          <p>HARO placements are genuine editorial citations — not paid links, not guest posts, not directory entries. Google treats them as the highest trust signal in its algorithm because they represent a third party voluntarily citing your expertise. Placements in Forbes, Business Insider, and similar publications with DR 80-90 can have significant domain authority impact in 3-6 months.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why HARO matters for SEO</h2>
        <p>For most sites, the ceiling on guest posting is DR 50-60. HARO is one of the only tactics that reliably earns links from DR 70-90+ publications at zero cash cost:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Authority level.</strong> A single Forbes or Business Insider link can be worth more than 50 directory links in terms of domain authority signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Editorial trust signal.</strong> Google's Quality Rater Guidelines reward E-E-A-T (Experience, Expertise, Authoritativeness, Trustworthiness). Being cited as an expert source directly demonstrates all four.</li>
          <li><strong>Brand visibility.</strong> Placements in major publications reach audiences that will never find you through search — creating brand awareness that precedes and multiplies organic search performance.</li>
          <li><strong>Zero cash investment.</strong> Unlike paid PR or sponsored content, HARO links cost only time and expertise. An hour per day responding to queries can generate 4-8 placements per month.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding authority.</strong> Early placements make journalists more likely to cite you again — journalists build source lists from prior credible sources.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How HARO works — step by step</h2>
        <p>The process runs on a daily cycle. Here is how a HARO placement happens from query to backlink:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># The HARO cycle</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Step 1:</span> Journalist posts a query with deadline (usually 24-48h)<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">Step 2:</span> HARO/Connectively sends query digest to registered sources<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">Step 3:</span> Source responds with expert quote + bio + website URL<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">Step 4:</span> Journalist selects best responses for article<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">Step 5:</span> Article publishes with attribution link to source's site<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-label">Step 6:</span> Google crawls publication, passes link equity to your domain
        </div>

        <h3>What makes a winning response</h3>
        <p>Journalists are on deadline. They scan responses in seconds. A response that wins a placement has these characteristics:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Subject line matches the query exactly</strong> — don't be clever, be findable</li>
          <li><strong>Opens with the quotable line</strong> — your best insight in the first two sentences</li>
          <li><strong>Includes a specific number, statistic, or framework</strong> — general advice is not cited; specific claims are</li>
          <li><strong>Brief bio establishing credibility</strong> — title, company, years of experience, one relevant achievement</li>
          <li><strong>Website URL clearly visible</strong> — journalists cannot link what they cannot find</li>
          <li><strong>Sent within 1-2 hours of query publication</strong> — journalists stop reading after they have enough responses</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Types of HARO queries — what to target</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Query type</th><th>Example</th><th>Placement DA range</th><th>Difficulty</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
