                <td><strong>Expert opinion</strong></td>
                <td>"What is the biggest SEO mistake small businesses make?"</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">DR 50-90+</td>
                <td>Low — any practitioner can answer</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Data request</strong></td><td>"What percentage of your leads come from organic search?"</td><td class="cell-yes">DR 60-90</td><td>Low if you have real data</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product/service test</strong></td><td>"Seeking small business owners who use CRM tools"</td><td class="cell-meh">DR 30-60</td><td>Medium — requires real user experience</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Research study source</strong></td><td>"Academic or research background in consumer behaviour"</td><td class="cell-yes">DR 70-90</td><td>High — requires credentials</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Story subject</strong></td><td>"Entrepreneur who scaled from 0 to $1M in revenue"</td><td class="cell-meh">DR 40-80</td><td>Medium — requires compelling narrative</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real HARO placement examples</h2>
        <p>Three scenarios showing how different types of practitioners use HARO effectively:</p>

        <h3>1. SaaS founder — expert opinion placement</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Query: "What makes email marketing campaigns fail?"</span><br>
          Response sent: <span class="uf-new">within 45 minutes of query email</span><br>
          Content: specific 3-point framework with percentage stat from internal data<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Placed in Business Insider article (DR 88)<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Keyword "email marketing tips" moved from position 14 to position 7 within 6 weeks
        </div>

        <h3>2. Local business owner — community story</h3>
        <p>A Denver bakery owner responded to a query about "small businesses that survived the pandemic" with a specific timeline of how they pivoted to delivery. The resulting article in a Denver lifestyle publication (DR 42) drove 380 referral visits and a do-follow local backlink — exactly the local authority signal Google Local Pack rankings need.</p>

        <h3>3. What a failed response looks like</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># What gets ignored</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">Sent 18 hours after query posted</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">Opening: "As a marketing professional with experience in..."</span><br>
          <span class="uf-old">No specific stats, no concrete framework, no memorable line</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-old">0 placements from 30 responses</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">HARO vs. guest posting — which builds better links?</h2>
        <p>Both are legitimate link-building tactics. Which one you prioritise depends on your goal and available time.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>HARO advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Access to DA 70-90+ publications impossible via guest post</li>
              <li>Zero cash cost — only time investment</li>
              <li>Links are genuine editorial citations</li>
              <li>Builds expert reputation alongside SEO value</li>
              <li>Journalist relationships compound over time</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Guest posting advantages</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Anchor text control — you choose the link text</li>
              <li>Consistent monthly link velocity possible</li>
              <li>Predictable topic relevance</li>
              <li>Easier to target specific DA ranges</li>
              <li>Full article content under your control</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for HARO that actually get placements</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Set up email alerts for query digests.</strong> Use Gmail filters or a dedicated inbox to flag HARO emails. Respond within 60 minutes of each digest arriving. After 2-3 hours, journalists have typically received enough responses.</li>
          <li><strong>Only respond to queries where you have genuine expertise.</strong> Journalists fact-check sources. Responding to queries outside your knowledge area wastes time and risks damaging relationships if you are selected and cannot support the claim.</li>
          <li><strong>Lead with your most specific, quotable insight.</strong> The best opening line is a claim that sounds counterintuitive but is defensible: "Most businesses lose 40% of their email list value not from unsubscribes but from hard bounces they never clean."</li>
          <li><strong>Include one real number from your own experience.</strong> "We reduced client churn by 22% using X" beats "reducing churn is important" every time. AI cannot generate real data — that is your competitive advantage as a source.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep bio to 2-3 sentences.</strong> Title, company, one relevant achievement. Journalists don't read long bios — they copy-paste the short credential into the article.</li>
          <li><strong>Follow up on published articles.</strong> Monitor HARO placements with Google Alerts and Ahrefs. Thank journalists who feature you — they build source lists and may reach out directly for future stories.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — responding to every query</div>
          <p>Many HARO beginners respond to 10-20 queries per day with generic answers, hoping volume produces results. This doesn't work. Journalists notice low-quality sources and mentally deprioritise them. Send 3-5 genuinely expert responses per day and your conversion rate will be 10x higher than sending 20 mediocre ones.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common HARO mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Responding after the deadline</strong> — queries typically close within 24-48 hours, and journalists stop reading much sooner. Time is the primary filter.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic responses without a specific claim</strong> — "I've worked in marketing for 10 years and think this is important" earns no placements.</li>
          <li><strong>Pitching your product instead of your expertise</strong> — HARO is for expert sources, not press releases. Journalists immediately recognise and reject promotional responses.</li>
          <li><strong>Not including a website URL</strong> — the entire point is the backlink. If you don't include your URL clearly, a journalist who wants to cite you has to search for it — and often won't bother.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping follow-up tracking</strong> — many placements don't notify you. Set up Google Alerts for your name and company to catch mentions you might miss and confirm the backlink went live.</li>
        </ul>

